        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "Zend_Date offers different methods to help working with dates.\r\nOne of them is the \"subMonth\" method.\r\n\r\nI have been using this method to work trough dates and performing DB queries.\r\nFor example:\r\n{code}\r\n$date = new Zend_Date('2012-03-01 00:00:00');\r\n$lastMonth = $date->subMonth(1); \/\/Expected value is '2012-02-01 00:00:00'\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nThis works for every case, except when the date is 'YEAR-02-01 00:00:00'.\r\nIn the case the date is February 1st, the date returned it January 1st of the previous year.\r\n{code}\r\n$date = new Zend_Date('2012-02-01 00:00:00');\r\n$lastMonth = $date->subMonth(1); \/\/Resulted value is '2011-01-01 00:00:00'\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nInteresting fact is if you continue to iterate trough this, the date gets back to normal, but it will fail in every February 1st.\r\n{code}\r\n$date = new Zend_Date('2012-02-01 00:00:00');\r\nwhile ($months++ < 24) {\r\n    echo $date->toString('YYYY-MM-dd') . '<br>';\r\n    $date->subMonth(1);\r\n}\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nThis will output:\r\n{code}\r\n2012-02-01\r\n2011-01-01 << Wrong year\r\n2011-12-01\r\n2011-11-01\r\n...\r\n2011-03-01\r\n2011-02-01\r\n2010-01-01 << Wrong year\r\n2010-12-01\r\n2010-11-01\r\n...\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nI noticed others strange behaviors, but I was unable to replicate as this.\r\n\r\nThe file version is described as:\r\n* @version   $Id: Date.php 22713 2010-07-29 11:41:56Z thomas $\r\nIt's the version included in the Magento library.\r\n\r\nI have upgraded this component to the 1.11.10, and the problem seems to persists.\r\n* @version   $Id: Date.php 24108 2011-06-04 00:09:27Z freak $"
        },
